(Translated by Google) They helped me a lot when I lost my passport. I arrived with the emergency since my flight was the next day apart.
I did the paperwork they asked me VERY KINDLY
In case someone happens to lose or steal a passport, the steps to follow are:
1. Obtain and bring a copy of your departure flight or bus ticket
2. You have to get a Mexican birth certificate that they give you (15USD).
3. With the certificate you can fill out the Passport format (the one they always ask for everywhere), if you haven't had a passport before - it wasn't my case then you have to fill out an application
4. Fill out a form when they speak to the managers explaining how or where you lost or stolen. This is shown to the Consultant and he / she authorizes.
5. They already call you and take your picture. In less than 30 minutes you already have it in your hands.

All this was explained to me very well.
Finishing everything, I was able to get my pop-up passport in less than 2 hours from when I went to the exit police until I already had the passport in my hands.
Thanks to Edgar for the explanation and the man at the reception, both of them were showing me all the steps to follow.

< Text>
I am a pizza connoisseur!  I will travel for good pizza. Thankfully sometimes I have the luxury to do so. I'm grateful I had the means (13$) to buy their 13" (slim) pie.i had the vegetarian one with cream sauce. It was my first time here, i walked into this beautiful huge space and was immediately greeted with a "welcome in! " there was no pressure to hurry and order- we came in right before a long line started. They walked us through everything we needed to know about the ordering process and although they didn't have one veggie that was supposed to come on the pizza I ordered they offered any other topping I wanted. They were all so helpful and the pizza was perfect! Cornmeal dusted crust, super flavorful sauce, fresh toppings, hot right out of the oven. I'll be going back a lot. It's really nice to see an awesome spot like this open up in oak park.<//Text>

< review>
While the staff did an amazing job yesterday making us feel welcome and assisting my wife and I with t-shirts, the back half of the store was a mess. Boxes covered almost the entire back and when I asked why was the back wall blocked off the response was "We're overflowing with shipment boxes and we don't have space in the back room". This seems like a terrible working condition for the staff and even worse shopping experience for the customers. I left unsatisfied because I couldn't even see what I had originally come there to get in the back half because boxes we're stacked so high and wide. Overall, the staff was friendly, the environment was a cluttered and unsightly at best.<//review>

< review>
Our coffee pit stop today was at this location.  It is not visible like most franchises.  My mom had her usual, an Americano.  I tried TODAY's BREW:  Costa Rica LA Cascada Tarrazu Medium Roast.  The barista was nice to make me a fresh brew.

TARRAZU is a very famous coffee growing region offers different characteristics depending on sub-region in Costa Rica. Costa Rica is famous for their fine coffee beans.

This single origin beans was definitely smooth, full-medium bodied with caramel notes. It had a slight acidity to it which makes it a bit complex.  These days, I prefer complex because of variety of flavor profiles. Medium roast is a way to go.

Did not on CBTL website or the package if the beans are 100% responsibly sourced from farmers who cultivate their crops.</review>

Was happy with the customer service. This particular location is very clean and spacious compared to other Coffee Bean stores. There are little over 30 seats inside the store and about four tables right outside the building. This store provides a wide, lengthy table placed in the middle of the location for people using their laptops or studying. This store is attached to an apartment complex. The parking facility is located indoors and is also spacious. A few metered parking spots are available as well. However, free parking is only available up to an hour. In my experience, this can be a nuisance because I may tend to stay longer than an hour from time to time. Another pet peeve is that they do not accept payments from the mobile app.< /Review>

< Review>
This is a great store, for the most part. Plenty of items on the shelves and a friendly staff. Well stocked and organized.
The problem is the mask policy. They require a mask, which is good, but sitting in the parking lot watching people, about 10 percent had the mask pulled down, so that their nose was exposed, defeating the purpose of the mask, and No one was correcting them (profits before safety? ).  Even the kid who collects shopping carts was doing that.  Why bother with the mask if it doesn't cover your nose?
Speaking of shopping carts,  you have to wipe your own cart down. Safeway hasn't invested in a spray bottle of bleach and a rag for the cart collector to sanitize the carts, like other stores. This is disconcerting of you are taking the virus seriously......<//Review>

< Review>
I love their signature brand coffee and the staff is always very nice. Safeway is expensive,  and they play with prices. I do not like the fact that you have to have a club card to get a sale item at the sale price. No other stores make you do this.
The sales they offer sometimes are not sales at all. Example: soda is 3.99, they will put it on sale, but you have to buy 3 to get one for free. So they jack the price up 1.00. So now its buy 3 at 4.99 and get one for free. Regular price 3.99 X 4 = $15.96. Sale price 4.99 X 3 = $14.97. And you get one for free. Yes you saved a whole quarter per 6 pack of soda. But you HAVE to buy 4. Is spending almost $20 of your grocery budget really worth .25 cents in savings. Not for me.</Review>

< review>
4 stars solely because after a specific time of day, (9:00PM maybe?) they bar one set of doors for the entire half of the store. This is seriously irritating, considering many handicapped parking spots are on the opposite side of the store, and these people also move through the doors extremely slowly, creating a bottleneck in the flow of traffic and resulting in lines of angry shoppers piling up behind them, and possibly even creating a small fire hazard. We all know that they do it to prevent theft, but they already have cameras right at the exits staring you in the face as you leave, as well as a security guard, so please just let the rest of us, the huge majority that are law abiding citizens, utilize the doors that you have RIGHT THERE, it's likely to attract enough returning customers to more than make up for the occasional shoplifter. I really doubt that by shutting one set of doors, any potential thief has said "Whoa, too much work for me to walk to the other side of the store with this stolen bottle of vodka, I'll just pay for it after all." I can't see a situation that blocking one pair of doors is going to stop someone from proceeding with their plan to steal.<//review>
